In order to select the most appropriate model, we fitted the LC-BML model for $R = 1, 2, \ldots, 20$ response style segments, $S = 1,2,  \ldots, 12$ value segments, and $P = 1, 2$ dimensions. In total \Sexpr{20 * 12 * 2} different models were considered; however \Sexpr{nrow(dat) - sum(complete.cases(dat))} models did not converge in the allotted number of EM iterations (10 000) and were discarded. The EM algorithm is however only guaranteed to find a local optimum of the likelihood function. We therefore estimated each of these models for 20 different random starts to increase our chances of finding the global optimum. Only the start which resulted in the highest value of the likelihood function is retained. 
% A numerical convergence criterion of $10^{-5}$ was used.
<<hullplot, echo=FALSE, results='hide', fig.show = 'hide', fig.align='center', warning=FALSE, fig.cap="The maximized log-likelihood plotted against degrees-of-freedom for the models considered. Colours are assigned according to the number of response styles $R$ and item segments $S$ in the left and right panels respectively. The convex hull enclosing the cloud of points is also shown.", fig.width=6.5, fig.height=5,out.width="0.49\\textwidth", message=FALSE>>=
library(ggplot2)
dat$R <- factor(dat$R)
dat$S <- factor(dat$S)
dat2 <- na.omit(dat)
hull <- chull(dat2[, 1:2])
dathull <- dat2[hull, ]
dat2 <- dat2[-hull, ]

p2 <- ggplot(data = dat2, mapping = aes(x = x, y = y)) + 
  geom_point(data = dat2, alpha = 0.5, mapping = aes(colour = R), shape = 20, size = 2.2) +
  geom_line(data = dathull, mapping = aes(x = x, y = y), colour = "grey30") + 
  geom_point(data = dathull, size = 3, shape = 21, mapping = aes(fill = R)) +
  xlab("Degrees-of-freedom") + ylab("Log-likelihood") + theme_bw() + guides(colour = "none") 
print(p2)

p1 <- ggplot(data = dat2, mapping = aes(x = x, y = y)) + 
  geom_point(data = dat2, alpha = 0.5, mapping = aes(colour = S), shape = 20, size = 2.2) +
  geom_line(data = dathull, mapping = aes(x = x, y = y), colour = "grey30") + 
  geom_point(data = dathull, size = 3, shape = 21, mapping = aes(fill = S)) +
  xlab("Degrees-of-freedom") + ylab("Log-likelihood") + theme_bw() + guides(colour = "none") 
  # theme(panel.grid.major = element_blank(), panel.grid.minor = element_blank())
print(p1)

tmptab <- dathull[order(dathull$BIC), c(3:5, 1, 6)]
rownames(tmptab) <- NULL
require(xtable)
xtable(tmptab, digits = 0)
@

We plotted the maximized log-likelihood values against the model degrees-of-freedom for the \Sexpr{nrow(na.omit(dat))} models. The convex hull enclosing the cloud of points can then be determined. We reduced the model selection problem by considering only the models that lie on this hull, similar to the CHull prodecure of \citet{ceulemans2011}. These models can be considered to present a good trade-off between complexity and data fit. We selected the model with $R = 20$ response styles, $S = 7$ values segments and $P = 2$ dimensions from the remaining \Sexpr{length(hull)} models, since it is more parsimonious than the more complex models. Our chosen model obtained the fourth lowest BIC value, but used significantly fewer degrees-of-freedom than the other models in the top five, ranked according to BIC. We now proceed to describe and interpret the results from this model.

